    <br/>
	<div class="row">
	    <div class="span-two-thirds">
	        <div class="page-header">
	            <h2>
	                Jaggery Server
	            </h2>
	        </div>
	
	        <p>
	            Jaggery Server is the Runtime that host Jaggery applications.
	            <br/>  <br/>
	            It contains a management console, for Admins to manger (deploy, reload, stop and start) Jaggery Apps. Using the management console, admins can gather basic statistics about the
	            deployed applications.
	             <br/><br/>
	            Jaggery Server is powered by WSO2 carbon OSGi Runtime
	
	            <br/> <br/>
	            Management console can be accessed by <code>{http://localhost:9443/carbon}</code>
	        </p>
	        <img alt="Jaggery Management Console" src="images/j-mgt-console.png"/>
	
	    </div>
	</div>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="span16">
            <h2>How to Deploy a Jaggery App</h2>

            <p>In-order to compose a Jaggery script you have to make it a <span class="label notice"> .jag</span> extension.</p>

            <p>There are no restrictions for the directory structure, add your <code>.jag</code> files where ever you want,
            zip them all together, rename the .zip to .war <b>(Just for now
                in M3)</b> and deploy at <i>{JAGGERY_HOME}/repository/deployment/server/jaggeryapps</i>
            </p>
            
            <p>Also Jaggery app .war file can be uploaded through the management console as follows. This can be found under Add link in Jaggery Applications section.</p>
            <br/>
            <img alt="Upload Jaggery" src="images/uploadjaggery.png"/>
        </div>
    </div>
    <br/>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="span-two-thirds">
            <div class="page-header">
                <h2>
                    Jaggery Command Line Client
                </h2>
            </div>

            <p>
                Jaggery command line client ships with the Jaggery bundle. Execute bin/jaggery.bat or bin/jaggery.sh
                based on your platform to enter into the command line console.
            </p>
            <img alt="Jaggery Command Line" src="images/commandline.png"/>
        </div>
    </div>
    <br/>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="span-two-thirds">
            <div class="page-header">
                <h2>
                    Command Line Commands
                </h2>
            </div>
            <p><code>&#60script.jag&#62</code> &#150 Load Jaggery script from the current path.</p>
            <p><code>&#60filepath&#47script.jag&#62</code> &#150 Load Jaggery script from the path given.</p>
            <img alt="Jaggery Commands" src="images/load.png"/>

            <p><code>-help</code> &#150 Shows all the commands for help.</p>

            <p><code>-quit</code> &#150 Quits the Jaggery command line (Only applicable for shell mode).</p>
            
            <p><code>-shell</code> &#150 Enter into the shell mode (shell mode is described in the next section).</p>
            
            <p><code>-version</code> &#150 Shows the current version of the Jaggery build.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <br/>
    <div class="row">
    <div class="span-two-thirds">
        <div class="page-header">
            <h2>
                Command Line Shell Mode
            </h2>
        </div>
        <p>
        	Jaggery command line shell mode will facilitate the evaluation of realtime Jaggery expressions. Also this will be
        	helpful for interactive shell executions.
        </p>

        <img alt="Jaggery Shell" src="images/shell.png"/>

        <p><code>help</code> &#150 Shows all the commands for help.</p>

        <p><code>quit</code> &#150 Quits the Jaggery command line (Only applicable for shell mode).</p>

        <p><code>version</code> &#150 Shows the current version of the Jaggery build.</p>
    </div>
